
T1 findings validated. The T1 did a thorough and accurate analysis of this rule.
The FireEye email detection side of the rule functions and returns results (screenshot attached showing 15 events with file names and email metadata over 24 hours). However, the CrowdStrike filewrite correlation does not work and has never worked.
Findings:
The base search against index=edr_extended with signature=filewritten times out at the 10 min max run time with 0 results (screenshot attached). The rule references nt_host in the stats command but this field does not exist in crowdstrike:events:sensor for filewritten events. Confirmed by searching 3.1 million events over 15 minutes with stats BY nt_host returning 0 results (screenshot attached). The dest field used in stats BY dest also does not exist in this sourcetype. 503 million events scanned, 0 statistics returned (screenshot attached).
The append re-queries the same FireEye data a second time because the subsearch discards all context fields. Since the CrowdStrike base search always times out, the only data reaching the stats command is the appended FireEye data. The rule is scoring risk purely on FireEye email alerts with action=allowed and no endpoint validation.
79 risk events generated in the last 30 days across 73 users at 69 points each, including ProofPoint service accounts (emailcbproofpointpatrolext@wellsfargo.com, proofpointvendorfilter@wellsfargo.com). src=unknown in all 79 events. No internal ProofPoint ESP traffic exclusion exists.
The security domain is set to Network. This rule’s stated intent is to detect file execution on a host after email delivery. That is endpoint behavior and should be classified under Endpoint.
Additional issues: duplicate entity row with risk score 0, annotations/confidence/impact all blank despite MITRE mapping to T1566.001/TA0001, drilldown only queries FireEye with no endpoint pivot.
Recommendation: Disable this rule. It requires a full rebuild to fix the CrowdStrike correlation (correct field mapping, proper join logic instead of append, scoped base search). In its current state it is generating non-actionable risk attributions against internal email security infrastructure.
